<font color="#FF0000">TO DOC DEL</font><br>
<tt>Sun May 11 21:38:23 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Doc Del,<br><br>
I think that healing may occur when one realizes that he can depend on others to help with the burden. Sometimes it is a hard thing to face - ALLOWING others to help. Admitting that the burden is too great. But, it is a good feeling to know that others WILL help.<br><br>
I had been in Vietnam for several months and had lost alot of weight. I couldn't eat anything out of the c rations except for crackers and peanut butter and maybe a few other things. The meals were more reminiscent of dog food than anything else. I had a very bad case of diarrhea. The heat was almost unbearable. The water in our canteens was barely fit to drink. I just couldn't go any furthur. I fell out. The entire company came to a halt. When word got out that I was sick, several guys came and lightened my pack. I was left with a rifle and ammo and an empty ruck sack. When we got to our night laager, a guy named Bob Landis, one of my Chicago homeboys, made me the C ration spaghetti (I can't recall if it had meat balls) and he put Louisiana Hot Sauce on it. I had never eaten hot sauce before. It was delicious. Years later, whenever we got together in Chicago, I always toasted Landis, or made mention of the &quot;time he saved my life&quot;. He knew that I meant it. The mental strain of Vietnam was tremendous. His act of kindness kept me going for another day. He'd always say how I would have done the same for him.<br><br>
Simple things like that stick with you. You never forget them. We were there for each other then, and we still are today. Not just vets for other vets. It should be people for other people.<br><br>
A kind word can go a long way.<br><br>
As for the numbness you felt for the child, I know of others who have experienced the same lack of sensation. Healed? I don't know.<br><br>
What I do know is that we should keep driving forward and never ever quit. <br><br>

<p><code>-- wingman@greene.xtn.net  (Tom Dier) </code><p>


